For the last year and a half or so, I've been training a neural network.

00:00:10.260 --> 00:00:11.260
And her name is Joy.

00:00:11.260 --> 00:00:15.480
This is my daughter.

00:00:15.480 --> 00:00:16.480
Joy is great.

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:19.799
Over the last, you know, over the time that I've been raising her, I've learned a lot

00:00:19.799 --> 00:00:20.799
of things.

00:00:20.799 --> 00:00:25.120
And one of the things I've learned is that the toys, the clothes, the activities that

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:29.120
work today, you cannot trust to work tomorrow.

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:32.119
She grows out of things really quickly.

00:00:32.119 --> 00:00:37.380
But some of the things that I love the best are the things that grow up with her.

00:00:37.380 --> 00:00:40.040
Because that means I don't have to go out and buy a bunch of new stuff.

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:41.040
So I don't know.

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:45.419
Here's that little blue ball that she's still playing with to this day.

00:00:45.419 --> 00:00:51.220
As much as I love to keep sharing baby photos, this talk, surprise, is about data.

00:00:51.220 --> 00:00:58.480
As your data grows and as your workflow size grows over time, and kind of outside of what

00:00:58.480 --> 00:01:04.360
your laptop can handle, you want a good tool that grows with you.

00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:10.139
Because you don't want to be in the situation where none of your clothes fit, basically,

00:01:10.139 --> 00:01:13.180
and all of your options kind of seem insurmountable.

00:01:13.180 --> 00:01:16.000
You can't run anything on your laptop.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:18.080
So how do we solve that problem?

00:01:18.080 --> 00:01:20.000
That's what today's talk is about.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:25.320
And I have a tool that I know grows with you really well, and that's Positron, as you probably

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:26.320
guessed.

