chart, which I will talk through for the rest of the talk, obviously.

00:01:53.839 --> 00:01:59.879
What do you do in the situation where you are running out of memory or time when you're

00:01:59.879 --> 00:02:02.199
running your workflows on your laptop?

00:02:02.199 --> 00:02:06.599
I'm going to talk a little bit about modern data processing tooling, how that might help

00:02:06.599 --> 00:02:07.599
you.

00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:10.639
I'm going to talk a little bit about a feature that I work on that I'm really excited about

00:02:10.639 --> 00:02:16.399
called Positron Remote SSH, which now that I say it out loud, sounds really sci-fi.

00:02:16.399 --> 00:02:17.399
But it's not.

00:02:17.399 --> 00:02:18.399
It's regular.

00:02:19.399 --> 00:02:23.520
And then I also want to give a call out to Posit Workbench, which has been mentioned

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:29.679
before, but it's our enterprise solution that I think adds a lot of features as well.

00:02:29.679 --> 00:02:32.399
So let's talk about modern data processing tooling.

00:02:32.399 --> 00:02:34.600
Basically, who is this for?

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:40.399
I think this is for people like all the people at my sister's wedding who are computational

00:02:40.399 --> 00:02:47.279
biologists and were assigned laptops by their organization that they call, quote, crappy

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:52.559
and need to run their R scripts for weeks on end and making sure that their laptop is

00:02:52.559 --> 00:02:54.839
connected to a power source.

00:02:54.839 --> 00:02:59.839
This is for people who don't have access to any other machines and are confined to their

00:02:59.839 --> 00:03:00.839
laptop.

00:03:00.839 --> 00:03:04.259
It might also be for people who maybe have access to other stuff, but they're working

00:03:04.259 --> 00:03:08.360
really quickly on quick local iterations or proof of concepts.

00:03:08.360 --> 00:03:13.559
This is kind of a different way of thinking how to do data processing.

00:03:13.559 --> 00:03:17.360
But I want to point out that these techniques are always useful, no matter your scenario.

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:22.639
So I would consider I would definitely consider learning these kinds of things as you walk

00:03:22.639 --> 00:03:24.600
away from this talk.

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:29.240
So as an example, throughout this talk, I'm going to work with the NYC taxi data set.

00:03:29.240 --> 00:03:30.960
Some of you might be familiar with this.

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:36.199
This is a lot bigger than Iris or Penguins, but it's basically all the trips that New

00:03:36.199 --> 00:03:39.279
York City taxis have taken since 2009.

00:03:39.279 --> 00:03:43.679
The one that I'm using is hosted by Ursa Labs, and that's a data set in parquet format

00:03:43.679 --> 00:03:48.559
that goes up until it's ten years of data, 2019, lives in the cloud.

00:03:48.559 --> 00:03:53.279
It's about 36 gigabytes on disk, and if you were to read it all into pandas in Python,

00:03:53.279 --> 00:03:56.839
that would be 400 gigabytes of RAM, and I don't know about you, but my MacBook does

00:03:56.839 --> 00:04:01.000
not have 400 gigabytes of RAM.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:02.440
So what can you do in this scenario?

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:06.240
I mean, luckily for you, there are a lot of tools that help with this.

00:04:06.240 --> 00:04:08.479
I put up some logos here on the slides.

00:04:08.479 --> 00:04:12.559
You've got DuckDB, Polars, Apache Spark, Dask.

00:04:12.559 --> 00:04:14.600
Python and R work with a lot of these.

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:18.200
The purpose of this talk is not which one to choose, because often that's determined

00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:24.279
by whatever your organization is using or, you know, different pros and cons between

00:04:24.279 --> 00:04:28.519
these things, but instead I want to focus on their similarities.

00:04:28.519 --> 00:04:30.679
So they typically use these strategies.

00:04:30.679 --> 00:04:37.279
The first one is deferred evaluation or lazy evaluation, just like these cats, and basically

00:04:37.279 --> 00:04:42.440
that means you don't query the data until the last possible second, and that's good

00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:47.839
because you don't want a bunch of intermediate data sets living in your laptop's memory and

00:04:47.839 --> 00:04:50.720
crashing your process, right?

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:52.720
This is that's really nice for working on queries.

00:04:52.720 --> 00:04:57.920
We also have a strategy called predicate pushdown or column reading, which is you only read

00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:00.040
the data that you need.

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:04.000
It's really helpful if you have data, for example, in parquet formats that's partitioned

00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:10.440
Because when you write a query, and, again, this can be in Python, R, SQL, or anything.

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:16.239
When you write a query, it can only access the data that it needs in order to execute

00:05:16.239 --> 00:05:17.239
that query.

00:05:17.239 --> 00:05:21.839
So if you have a million row or million column parquet file and you only need access to a

00:05:21.839 --> 00:05:26.720
few of those columns for the query that you're doing, you're reading, it only reads those

00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:30.000
columns, and in some cases, if your parquet file is partitioned the right way, it only

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:34.200
reads certain rows from that file as well.

00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:36.839
And that's good because you're not wasting time reading a bunch of data that you don't

00:05:36.839 --> 00:05:37.839
need.

00:05:37.839 --> 00:05:42.559
And then finally, these libraries and tools, they split the work among multiple processors

00:05:42.559 --> 00:05:43.559
if possible.

00:05:43.559 --> 00:05:48.799
So if your laptop or any computer you're working on has multiple CPUs or maybe even GPUs or

00:05:48.799 --> 00:05:55.480
VCPUs, whatever, it's going to split up that work, parallelize it, and make things faster.

00:05:55.480 --> 00:05:57.720
So that's great.

00:05:57.720 --> 00:06:01.279
I'm going to go through a demo today in Python.

00:06:01.279 --> 00:06:03.839
I like the Ibis library.

00:06:03.839 --> 00:06:04.920
Hopefully some of you have heard of it.

00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:08.600
Ibis in Python I think of as a universal adapter.

00:06:08.600 --> 00:06:16.720
So it's a data frame library, it's verbs, it's syntax is very similar to dplyr and R.

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:20.839
And basically you can connect to any of these backends.

00:06:20.839 --> 00:06:25.119
And that's what I'm doing here at the top of this slide is this is a bunch of different

00:06:25.119 --> 00:06:26.880
ways to connect to different backends, right?

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:30.399
I'm connecting to DuckDB, Polars, PySpark, Postgres.

00:06:30.399 --> 00:06:34.640
Once you have the connection details stored in your connection object, then you use that

00:06:34.640 --> 00:06:40.000
connection object to define a table that you work with or a data frame.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:41.640
That's what I'm doing in the second part of the slide.

00:06:41.640 --> 00:06:44.480
I'm reading these Parquet files that live in the cloud.

00:06:44.480 --> 00:06:50.559
I'm saying, hey, go to Amazon S3, read the Ursa Labs taxi bucket, and look at all of

00:06:50.559 --> 00:06:53.320
those Parquet files metadata.

00:06:53.320 --> 00:06:55.320
Call it NYC taxi.

00:06:55.320 --> 00:06:56.320
And there you go.

00:06:56.320 --> 00:07:02.079
You can manipulate these Parquet files just by referring to this table.

