Again, if I were to read this in as a CSV, it would definitely crash my Python process.

00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:42.960
Yeah, that's pretty big, and that count query was actually really fast, too, because it's

00:08:42.960 --> 00:08:45.479
just reading the metadata of these Parquet files.

00:08:45.479 --> 00:08:46.479
All right.

00:08:46.479 --> 00:08:50.640
Next, I want to do an actual query that you might use for, I don't know, EDA or something.

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:55.799
Let's say I have the question, I want to find the mean tip percentage grouped by the number

00:08:55.799 --> 00:09:01.380
of passengers in the taxi, but only look at the data where the total price was greater

00:09:01.380 --> 00:09:02.719
than $100, right?

00:09:02.719 --> 00:09:05.919
So this is the query that I would construct in Ibis.

00:09:05.919 --> 00:09:10.039
What you'll see, maybe, if you can read it, is that Ibis has a lot of verbs that are very

00:09:10.039 --> 00:09:11.840
Dplyr familiar, right?

00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:14.640
So I've got filter, select, mutate.

00:09:14.640 --> 00:09:20.479
The filter that I'm using, this first one, I'm filtering the timestamp to January of

00:09:20.479 --> 00:09:25.159
2009, and the reason I'm doing this is because this is my local laptop, and I'm reading data

00:09:25.159 --> 00:09:28.520
over the Internet, and I don't want it to take too long for this demo, right?

00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:33.719
So when I filter it to only January of 2009, what that means is when I actually execute

00:09:33.719 --> 00:09:39.159
the query, it only reads the Parquet file that contains that data for January 2009,

00:09:39.159 --> 00:09:44.440
and it's going to skip the rest of the Parquet files, which is, again, nice so that I don't

00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:48.719
have to wait for the query to execute over the Internet.

00:09:48.719 --> 00:09:52.679
Next I'm going to filter to the total amount, greater than 100, the passenger count is greater

00:09:52.679 --> 00:09:57.640
than zero, just to exclude some outliers or bad data, right?

00:09:57.640 --> 00:09:59.039
This is just very typical stuff, right?

00:09:59.039 --> 00:10:05.320
I'll select some columns, I'll add a column, I'll group by passenger count, add some aggregated

00:10:05.320 --> 00:10:09.440
columns and mutate, again, add another column.

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:12.200
So let's execute this query, and that was instantaneous, right?

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:14.479
Because, again, this is lazy evaluation.

00:10:14.479 --> 00:10:18.520
It's not going to actually look at the data until I ask it to.

00:10:18.520 --> 00:10:21.880
Finally, I execute my ggplot code, right?

