00:11:59.739 --> 00:12:03.460
Next I want to talk about, again, I think one of the most undervalued features of Positron,

00:12:03.460 --> 00:12:05.500
which is remote SSH.

00:12:05.500 --> 00:12:07.500
So SSH stands for secure shell.

00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:11.219
If you haven't heard of it, it's a way to connect to a local machine.

00:12:11.219 --> 00:12:14.299
This is for people who have access to another machine, right?

00:12:14.299 --> 00:12:18.619
This could be anything from a spare computer you've got laying around your house to a high‑performance

00:12:18.619 --> 00:12:21.900
cluster that your organization has set up in the cloud.

00:12:21.900 --> 00:12:25.260
Or it's for people who don't have one today, but they could set one up if they wanted to

00:12:25.260 --> 00:12:26.380
and maintain it, right?

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:31.659
So they might set up an EC2 instance on Amazon or a VM of some sort.

00:12:31.659 --> 00:12:33.820
I've seen this a lot in scrappy data science teams.

00:12:33.820 --> 00:12:39.340
I was on one at a weather company in a previous job where we had, you know, terabytes of data

00:12:39.340 --> 00:12:44.179
to analyze because we're trying to predict the weather all over the globe.

00:12:44.179 --> 00:12:49.059
And you just can't read terabytes of data over the Internet all the time, in my opinion.

00:12:49.059 --> 00:12:55.140
So we have ‑‑ we had a VM set up that we mounted that data set to, which basically

00:12:55.140 --> 00:12:59.739
just meant that whenever it read that data, it didn't have to talk over the Internet.

00:12:59.739 --> 00:13:04.140
It was in the same data center, and the reads were so much faster because it looked like

00:13:04.140 --> 00:13:08.719
you were just reading from the same file system, right?

00:13:08.719 --> 00:13:10.200
How does remote SSH work?

00:13:10.200 --> 00:13:14.820
Let me point out that, by the way, this is completely free, right?

00:13:14.820 --> 00:13:17.859
So this comes shipped with Positron Desktop.

00:13:17.859 --> 00:13:24.900
All you need to do is install Positron Desktop, and if you have access to this remote machine,

00:13:24.900 --> 00:13:28.659
this should just work, theoretically, if you can SSH into that remote machine, which,

00:13:28.659 --> 00:13:32.419
you know, that's usually the hardest part is authentication, but once you have that

00:13:32.419 --> 00:13:35.419
figured out with your IT team, this should just work, right?

00:13:35.419 --> 00:13:40.299
So you go to your bottom left, you click open a remote window, you enter in your user, password,

00:13:40.299 --> 00:13:45.059
host name, you know, all that information, and then you click go, basically, and this

00:13:45.059 --> 00:13:46.700
is what pops up, right?

00:13:46.700 --> 00:13:51.260
So this looks a lot like the demo that I showed before, and that's the point, right?

00:13:51.260 --> 00:13:52.260
It is.

00:13:52.260 --> 00:13:53.619
It does look a lot.

00:13:53.619 --> 00:13:57.260
There are a few differences here that I've highlighted with the arrows, but basically

00:13:57.260 --> 00:14:02.500
all you see is that it highlights that you're using SSH mode, it's showing me the host name

00:14:02.500 --> 00:14:06.900
that I've connected to, but everything else is the same, and that's by design, right?

00:14:06.900 --> 00:14:12.020
So here's the architecture of remote SSH, what it's doing, if you allow me to nerd out

00:14:12.020 --> 00:14:15.979
for a second, on your local machine is just the UI, right?

00:14:15.979 --> 00:14:18.179
Like the pretty pixels that show up.

00:14:18.179 --> 00:14:21.140
On the remote machine is where you do all of your compute, right?

00:14:21.140 --> 00:14:26.219
So not only are your Python session or your R session happening on the remote machine,

00:14:26.219 --> 00:14:28.900
but your file system that you're working with is there.

00:14:28.900 --> 00:14:33.280
The Positron back end itself is also there, so we're running that extension host that

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:38.700
Jonathan mentioned on the remote machine, and that's great, because you can take full

00:14:38.700 --> 00:14:43.140
advantage of your more beefy machine's capabilities.

